<i>All I wanted to do</i>
<i>was play football.</i>

231
00:10:12.612 --> 00:10:14.364
<i>I mean. that was what I knew</i>

232
00:10:14.406 --> 00:10:16.074
<i>I wanted to do in college.</i>

233
00:10:17.450 --> 00:10:19.994
<i>I ended up going</i>
<i>to University of Minnesota.</i>

234
00:10:20.036 --> 00:10:22.205
Back then. they helped you
a lot with your academics--

235
00:10:22.247 --> 00:10:24.332
like. just go to class.
and you'll pass.

236
00:10:25.875 --> 00:10:27.961
<i>But I was just there for fun.</i>

237
00:10:28.003 --> 00:10:29.921
<i>I didn't give a damn</i>
<i>about school.</i>

238
00:10:31.339 --> 00:10:33.341
<i>I lived in a fraternity</i>
<i>That was the year after--</i>

239
00:10:33.383 --> 00:10:34.384
<i>after I flunked out.</i>

240
00:10:34.426 --> 00:10:35.343
<i>My parents didn't know.</i>

241
00:10:37.846 --> 00:10:40.849
- How did your parents react

242
00:10:40.890 --> 00:10:43.143
when you told 'em
you'd flunked out?

243
00:10:46.855 --> 00:10:48.982
- Uh. they weren't shocked.

244
00:10:49.024 --> 00:10:51.109
They weren't shocked.

245
00:10:51.151 --> 00:10:54.320
<i>I sold life insurance</i>
<i>for a year after that.</i>

246
00:10:54.362 --> 00:10:56.489
<i>I never got my license.</i>
<i>but I made 40 grand.</i>

247
00:10:56.531 --> 00:10:58.700
'cause I just introduced
all the general agents

248
00:10:58.742 --> 00:11:01.953
to my friends around town.
[laughs]

249
00:11:01.995 --> 00:11:04.205
I never actually
passed the test.

250
00:11:05.206 --> 00:11:07.834
<i>- In 1971. Richard Fliehr</i>

251
00:11:07.876 --> 00:11:10.003
<i>did make</i>
<i>a major life decision.</i>

252
00:11:10.045 --> 00:11:13.131
<i>He got married</i>
<i>for the first time.</i>

253
00:11:13.173 --> 00:11:14.758
- Leslie.
She's a wonderful lady.

254
00:11:14.799 --> 00:11:16.301
We get along to this day.

255
00:11:18.011 --> 00:11:20.722
<i>- The next year.</i>
<i>they had their first daughter.</i>

256
00:11:20.764 --> 00:11:22.182
<i>Megan.</i>

257
00:11:23.058 --> 00:11:26.186
<i>Now a father. Ric was trying</i>
<i>to find his way.</i>

258
00:11:26.227 --> 00:11:29.064
<i>searching</i>
<i>for his life's purpose.</i>

259
00:11:29.105 --> 00:11:32.275
<i>He found it</i>
<i>in a likely location:</i>

260
00:11:32.317 --> 00:11:33.234
<i>a bar.</i>

261
00:11:34.736 --> 00:11:37.072
- Ric Flair was working
as a bouncer

262
00:11:37.113 --> 00:11:40.492
<i>in the Minneapolis area.</i>

263
00:11:40.533 --> 00:11:41.868
<i>- So I'm bouncing.</i>

264
00:11:41.910 --> 00:11:43.286
and I'm sitting here
with my elbow

265
00:11:43.328 --> 00:11:44.996
on the cigarette machine.
on a stool. right?

266
00:11:45.038 --> 00:11:46.706
And in walks this guy.
and I look--

267
00:11:46.748 --> 00:11:48.500
[whispers] "Holy fuck."

268
00:11:48.541 --> 00:11:50.960
He's smoking a Salem cigarette

269
00:11:51.002 --> 00:11:53.546
and sits down
and orders a double vodka

270
00:11:53.588 --> 00:11:55.382
and a soda.

271
00:11:55.423 --> 00:11:58.426
I said.
"Fuck. that's Ken Patera."

272
00:11:58.468 --> 00:12:00.053
<i>- Ken Patera was</i>

273
00:12:00.095 --> 00:12:03.056
<i>a very fabled</i>
<i>Olympic weightlifter.</i>

274
00:12:03.098 --> 00:12:05.725
and this Olympian
starts engaging Ric Flair

275
00:12:05.767 --> 00:12:07.519
in conversation.

276
00:12:07.560 --> 00:12:09.229
- I walk over. and I say.
"You Ken Patera?"

277
00:12:09.270 --> 00:12:11.272
He said. "Yeah.
What's your name?"

278
00:12:11.314 --> 00:12:13.566
I said. "Ric.
Ric Fliehr."

279
00:12:13.608 --> 00:12:16.027
He goes. "How ya doing?
You know this town very well?"

280
00:12:16.069 --> 00:12:17.487
I said.
"Yeah. know it real well."

281
00:12:17.529 --> 00:12:20.824
- Before you know it.
Ric Flair and Ken Patera

282
00:12:20.865 --> 00:12:22.575
are living together.

283
00:12:22.617 --> 00:12:25.954
<i>and this Olympian.</i>
<i>who was actually training</i>

284
00:12:25.995 --> 00:12:27.914
for the professional
wrestling world.

285
00:12:27.956 --> 00:12:30.667
was being sponsored
by Verne Gagne.

286
00:12:30.709 --> 00:12:33.795
<i>- Here's wrestling champion</i>
<i>Verne Gagne.</i>

287
00:12:33.837 --> 00:12:37.257
- Well. here I am.
What's up?

288
00:12:37.298 --> 00:12:39.926
<i>- Verne Gagne was the promoter</i>

289
00:12:39.968 --> 00:12:44.305
for the American
Wrestling Association. or AWA.

290
00:12:44.347 --> 00:12:47.892
<i>which was</i>
<i>a Minneapolis-based promotion.</i>

291
00:12:47.934 --> 00:12:50.145
Every year.
Verne Gagne would put

292
00:12:50.186 --> 00:12:52.564
a class of trainees together.

293
00:12:52.605 --> 00:12:54.149
- You still have the same shock
that you had

294
00:12:54.190 --> 00:12:56.443
the first time
someone threw you down.

295
00:12:56.484 --> 00:12:59.487
<i>but you're building up</i>
<i>a tolerance to it.</i>

296
00:12:59.529 --> 00:13:02.699
<i>- Well. I went to the camp.</i>
<i>enthusiastic as possible.</i>

297
00:13:02.741 --> 00:13:05.160
<i>but I had no idea what I was</i>
<i>getting myself into.</i>

298
00:13:05.201 --> 00:13:07.662
That--two months
with those guys.

299
00:13:07.704 --> 00:13:09.205
legs were chafed.
I couldn't walk.

300
00:13:09.247 --> 00:13:11.124
I mean. Gagne. you know.
came over and got me.

301
00:13:11.166 --> 00:13:12.417
slapped me across the face.

302
00:13:12.459 --> 00:13:14.294
- You don't just
walk out there.

303
00:13:14.336 --> 00:13:15.211
pick him up and lay him down.
We wanna see some action.

304
00:13:15.253 --> 00:13:16.421
wanna see what you can do.

305
00:13:16.463 --> 00:13:17.464
I trained him.

306
00:13:17.505 --> 00:13:18.506
<i>I'd start 'em out</i>

307
00:13:18.548 --> 00:13:19.507
<i>with just knee bends.</i>

308
00:13:19.549 --> 00:13:20.800
<i>and we'd do 50</i>

309
00:13:20.842 --> 00:13:22.010
<i>to 100 knee bends.</i>

310
00:13:22.052 --> 00:13:24.471
Well. the guys--you know.
at 50.

311
00:13:24.512 --> 00:13:26.014
they fell on their face.

312
00:13:26.056 --> 00:13:27.390
- Ugh. it was brutal.

313
00:13:27.432 --> 00:13:30.143
That was a--
I mean. first of all.

314
00:13:30.185 --> 00:13:32.354
<i>I was 300 pounds.</i>
<i>I mean. to this day.</i>

315
00:13:32.395 --> 00:13:34.064
<i>you take a good athlete</i>
<i>and tell him to do</i>

316
00:13:34.105 --> 00:13:39.778
500 free squats.
250 push-ups. 200 crunches.

317
00:13:39.819 --> 00:13:42.072
- 200.

318
00:13:42.113 --> 00:13:44.407
<i>- And run two miles.</i>

319
00:13:44.449 --> 00:13:47.660
<i>How many good athletes</i>
<i>can do that right now?</i>

320
00:13:47.702 --> 00:13:50.080
Like 1%?
Think about it.

321
00:13:50.121 --> 00:13:52.665
And we're doing this
in 30-degree weather outside.

322
00:13:52.707 --> 00:13:54.668
<i>- Come on. dig. dig. dig. dig!</i>

323
00:13:54.709 --> 00:13:56.503
<i>* *</i>

324
00:13:56.544 --> 00:13:59.172
<i>- He was training hard</i>
<i>to become a pro wrestler.</i>

325
00:13:59.214 --> 00:14:02.008
<i>but step one</i>
<i>in Fliehr's metamorphosis</i>

326
00:14:02.050 --> 00:14:05.220
<i>into the character</i>
<i>began with a new name...</i>

327
00:14:06.638 --> 00:14:09.641
Ric Flair.
- Mm-hmm.

328
00:14:09.683 --> 00:14:11.351
- Where did the name come from?

329
00:14:11.393 --> 00:14:12.686
- Verne.

330
00:14:12.727 --> 00:14:14.062
<i>I was so enamored</i>

331
00:14:14.104 --> 00:14:15.814
<i>with Dusty Rhodes.</i>

332
00:14:15.855 --> 00:14:18.441
I said I wanted to call myself
Rambling Ricky Rhodes.

333
00:14:18.483 --> 00:14:19.943
He got up.
threw his glasses down.

334
00:14:19.984 --> 00:14:21.528
and said.
"Rambling Ricky Rhodes?

335
00:14:21.569 --> 00:14:24.114
"What is it with you
and Dusty Rhodes?

336
00:14:24.155 --> 00:14:26.449
"Your name is Ric Flair.
That's fucking cool as shit--

337
00:14:26.491 --> 00:14:27.742
Ric Flair."

338
00:14:27.784 --> 00:14:29.244
I said. "It is?"
He said. "Yeah.

339
00:14:29.285 --> 00:14:31.204
just call yourself Ric Flair.
Change the spot."

340
00:14:31.246 --> 00:14:33.415
<i>[bell dings]</i>
<i>[crowd cheering]</i>

341
00:14:33.456 --> 00:14:37.877
<i>I had my first match.</i>
<i>Minneapolis Auditorium.</i>

342
00:14:37.919 --> 00:14:39.546
<i>ten minute draw.</i>

343
00:14:39.587 --> 00:14:42.173
<i>longest ten minutes</i>
<i>of my life.</i>

344
00:14:42.215 --> 00:14:46.302
<i>I was excited about it. but I</i>
<i>didn't know what I was doing.</i>

345
00:14:46.344 --> 00:14:48.388
- What did you make
for your first match?

346
00:14:48.430 --> 00:14:49.347
- 50 bucks.

347
00:14:50.974 --> 00:14:55.645
I spent it coming home.
[laughs]

348
00:14:55.687 --> 00:14:59.774
Man. I have driven 3.000 miles
for $210.

349
00:14:59.816 --> 00:15:03.695
<i>I would drive to Winnipeg.</i>
<i>500 each way.</i>

350
00:15:03.737 --> 00:15:06.740
drive back. get home
at 5:00 in the morning. right.

351
00:15:06.781 --> 00:15:08.950
and get up at noon
and leave for Des Moines. Iowa.

352
00:15:08.992 --> 00:15:11.119
<i>[percussive beat]</i>

353
00:15:11.161 --> 00:15:13.955
- In front of crowds
of how many?

354
00:15:13.997 --> 00:15:18.251
- Oh. probably--in Winnipeg.
it was almost always sold out.

355
00:15:18.293 --> 00:15:22.547
but everything else was. like.
50 and 100. maybe 150.

356
00:15:22.589 --> 00:15:24.716
but never--

357
00:15:24.758 --> 00:15:27.385
I just barely--we lived.
basically. off Leslie.

358
00:15:27.427 --> 00:15:30.472
<i>She was a dental hygienist.</i>

359
00:15:30.513 --> 00:15:32.557
<i>I didn't have the experience.</i>

360
00:15:32.599 --> 00:15:34.934
But once I got rolling.
I mean. I liked it so much

361
00:15:34.976 --> 00:15:36.644
that I--when I wasn't booked.

362
00:15:36.686 --> 00:15:38.438
<i>I would travel</i>
<i>with Dusty Rhodes</i>

363
00:15:38.480 --> 00:15:40.106
<i>and Dick Murdoch. just be</i>
<i>their driver.</i>

364
00:15:40.148 --> 00:15:42.359
<i>I drove Andre for two years</i>

365
00:15:42.400 --> 00:15:43.693
when he was Jean Ferre.

366
00:15:43.735 --> 00:15:45.195
He actually broke in

367
00:15:45.236 --> 00:15:47.072
<i>the same time</i>
<i>I was breaking in.</i>

368
00:15:47.113 --> 00:15:48.448
<i>and I drove him everywhere.</i>

369
00:15:48.490 --> 00:15:50.784
and when he'd get
to the building. he'd go.

370
00:15:50.825 --> 00:15:53.078
"Boss. get me wine."

371
00:15:53.119 --> 00:15:54.621
One day. David Crockett said.

372
00:15:54.662 --> 00:15:57.040
"No. no. no wine
till after the match."

373
00:15:57.082 --> 00:16:00.126
"Boss. there be no match.
Wine."

374
00:16:00.168 --> 00:16:01.544
Naw. there was that night

375
00:16:01.586 --> 00:16:03.797
he drank 106 beers
at The Downtowner.

376
00:16:03.838 --> 00:16:05.215
<i>Verne had me drive him.</i>
<i>It was great.</i>

377
00:16:05.256 --> 00:16:07.217
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

378
00:16:07.258 --> 00:16:09.344
<i>- Hanging out</i>
<i>with Andre the Giant.</i>

379
00:16:09.386 --> 00:16:11.429
<i>riding with Dusty Rhodes.</i>

380
00:16:11.471 --> 00:16:15.975
<i>Ric Flair was traveling</i>
<i>with the best in the business.</i>

381
00:16:16.017 --> 00:16:20.146
- So this is 1974.

382
00:16:20.188 --> 00:16:23.525
So I get invited to go
to the Carolinas. right?

383
00:16:23.566 --> 00:16:27.362
<i>And I'm married at this point.</i>
<i>and we had just had Megan.</i>

384
00:16:27.404 --> 00:16:29.030
<i>So I go to my dad.</i>

385
00:16:29.072 --> 00:16:31.032
I said. "Can I have $400
to go down there?"

386
00:16:33.368 --> 00:16:36.413
<i>So I flew down there</i>
<i>in April of '74</i>

387
00:16:36.454 --> 00:16:39.332
<i>with 200 bucks in my pocket.</i>

388
00:16:39.374 --> 00:16:41.543
<i>Left Leslie 200 bucks.</i>

389
00:16:41.584 --> 00:16:45.463
<i>* *</i>

390
00:16:45.505 --> 00:16:49.551
<i>And I'd met this guy in a bar.</i>

391
00:16:49.592 --> 00:16:52.512
<i>* *</i>

392
00:16:52.554 --> 00:16:54.764
<i>He said. "You're Ric Flair?"</i>
<i>And I said. "Yeah."</i>

393
00:16:54.806 --> 00:16:56.516
He said. "You guys ever
thought about flying?

394
00:16:56.558 --> 00:16:59.185
I hear you drive everywhere."
I said.

395
00:16:59.227 --> 00:17:01.062
"Yeah. I thought about it.
Why?"

396
00:17:01.104 --> 00:17:02.313
He said. "Well. I got a plane."

397
00:17:02.355 --> 00:17:04.274
I said. "You got a plane?"

398
00:17:04.315 --> 00:17:06.192
So I said. you know.
"What are you talking about?"

399
00:17:06.234 --> 00:17:08.445
He said.
"Well. there's five of you.

400
00:17:08.486 --> 00:17:10.613
I can carry five of you.
only charge you $100 apiece."

401
00:17:10.655 --> 00:17:13.158
I said.
"Only $100 apiece to fly?"

402
00:17:13.199 --> 00:17:14.242
I said. "How fast does it go?"

403
00:17:14.284 --> 00:17:16.119
He said. "250 miles an hour."

404
00:17:16.161 --> 00:17:17.871
I said. "You're kidding me.
$100 apiece?"

405
00:17:17.912 --> 00:17:19.330
So bingo.

406
00:17:19.372 --> 00:17:23.418
I got five people.
like. right away.

407
00:17:23.460 --> 00:17:25.712
<i>- So Ric Flair</i>
<i>and some of the other guys</i>

408
00:17:25.754 --> 00:17:27.839
<i>decided that they were</i>
<i>gonna pool their money</i>

409
00:17:27.881 --> 00:17:30.884
and hire a Vietnam veteran
who is a pilot

410
00:17:30.925 --> 00:17:32.427
to transport them

411
00:17:32.469 --> 00:17:35.555
around the Charlotte
wrestling territory.

412
00:17:35.597 --> 00:17:39.934
and this guy would load up
his plane with talent.

413
00:17:39.976 --> 00:17:43.563
and these were big dudes.
and it was a small plane.

414
00:17:43.605 --> 00:17:47.400
So now he had to compensate
for the extra weight.

415
00:17:47.442 --> 00:17:49.527
and he did that by dumping

416
00:17:49.569 --> 00:17:51.738
some of the fuel
from the plane.

417
00:17:51.780 --> 00:17:58.036
<i>* *</i>

418
00:17:58.078 --> 00:18:02.624
<i>- We were in</i>
<i>a six-passenger Cessna 310.</i>

419
00:18:02.665 --> 00:18:04.042
<i>* *</i>

420
00:18:04.084 --> 00:18:05.543
<i>We were flying to Wilmington</i>

421
00:18:05.585 --> 00:18:09.381
<i>for a night show on Sunday.</i>

422
00:18:09.422 --> 00:18:12.425
So we got to what's called
"the point of no return."

423
00:18:12.467 --> 00:18:14.469
which I've learned.

424
00:18:14.511 --> 00:18:17.722
In other words. he should've
refueled in Raleigh.

425
00:18:17.764 --> 00:18:20.684
We were 1.400 pounds
over gross.

426
00:18:20.725 --> 00:18:24.229
and so he compensated for that
by carrying less fuel.

427
00:18:24.270 --> 00:18:26.773
<i>All of a sudden.</i>
<i>we're at 6.000 feet.</i>

428
00:18:26.815 --> 00:18:30.026
<i>and we're just starting</i>
<i>to descend. and. uh.</i>

429
00:18:30.068 --> 00:18:31.277
all of a sudden.
the right engine.

430
00:18:31.319 --> 00:18:33.905
it went boop-boop-boop.

431
00:18:33.947 --> 00:18:35.740
I mean. it pinned.
Bingo.

432
00:18:35.782 --> 00:18:38.368
Within ten seconds.
it was dead. boom.

433
00:18:38.410 --> 00:18:41.037
Then he reached down--
I saw him grab--

434
00:18:41.079 --> 00:18:42.497
he pulled the reserve tanks.

435
00:18:42.539 --> 00:18:44.332
forgetting he didn't have
any reserve fuel.

436
00:18:44.374 --> 00:18:45.875
<i>* *</i>

437
00:18:45.917 --> 00:18:49.129
<i>So the left one</i>
<i>just went broop. boom.</i>

438
00:18:49.170 --> 00:18:51.256
and man. we're. you know.

439
00:18:51.297 --> 00:18:53.800
I would say
between 5.500 and 6.000 feet.

440
00:18:53.842 --> 00:18:54.801
I remember looking at it.

441
00:18:54.843 --> 00:18:56.803
<i>* *</i>

442
00:18:56.845 --> 00:19:00.974
<i>- And at this point.</i>
<i>there was real panic going on.</i>

443
00:19:01.016 --> 00:19:02.684
The pilot began to freak out.

444
00:19:02.726 --> 00:19:05.145
<i>and the great Johnny Valentine</i>

445
00:19:05.186 --> 00:19:06.396
<i>was sitting next to the pilot.</i>

446
00:19:06.438 --> 00:19:08.148
<i>and he. being a wrestler.</i>

447
00:19:08.189 --> 00:19:11.067
he figured. "Well.
I'll slap some sense into him."

448
00:19:11.109 --> 00:19:13.194
and he started
slapping the pilot

449
00:19:13.236 --> 00:19:15.363
to try to get him to focus.

450
00:19:15.405 --> 00:19:18.533
[plane whirring rapidly]

451
00:19:27.917 --> 00:19:31.212
[plane whirring rapidly]

452
00:19:31.254 --> 00:19:32.756
<i>- We were going so fast.</i>

453
00:19:32.797 --> 00:19:34.674
<i>probably</i>
<i>over 300 miles an hour.</i>

454
00:19:34.716 --> 00:19:37.052
that normally.
when you hit a tree orchard.

455
00:19:37.093 --> 00:19:39.220
a small plane--it would
cartwheel a small plane.

456
00:19:39.262 --> 00:19:42.349
We mowed the tree orchard down.

457
00:19:42.390 --> 00:19:44.893
- I think they barely missed
the water tower.

